<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Hes right. Africa and Central Asia dont have much to offer us. Doesnt make it right, but its the way things work.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Oh pardon me, here I was thinking that we should do the right thing, instead of the profitable thing. The question is, where do you draw the line? Or do you have a particular need for Rhode Island?<br>
<br>
I'm shocked and appalled to hear how you take it as a given , and apparently agree with, that this current war is about &quot;what we can get out of it&quot;.<br>
<br>
British Petroleum (BP) estimated the time that various countries' oil fields are expected to last (as of 2002):<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Iraq 128.98</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Kuwait 127.70<br>
United Arab Emirates 114.81<br>
Saudi Arabia 85.13<br>
Iran 67.25<br>
Azerbaijan 67.02<br>
Venezuela 63.58<br>
Qatar 55.57<br>
Other South and<br>
Central America 41.21<br>
Nigeria 30.41<br>
Syria 10.99 <br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>USA 10.52</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <br>
<br>
I don't know about you, but if we're running low on crude oil, I'd rather change my life style than have to live with pictures like:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.krysstal.com/images/iraq_29.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.krysstal.com/images/iraq_39.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
And if we were so keen on producing a lasting peace in the middle east, then I wonder why the US vetoed a resolution which called for a complete ban of nuclear weapons in the middle east in 1981?<br>
<br>
Would you care to see a list of UN resolutions vetoed and ignored by the US concerning the middle east?<br>
<br>
Let's face it, if the world production of oranges came from the middle east, we couldn't care less about them. It's for reasons like this why our democracies are falling apart.<br>
<br>
People accept the fact that everything's done because of profitable reasons, rather than what's right and wrong. People accept that politicians are crooks and liars.<br>
<br>
If you send your soldiers into battle and some of them into certain death, I suggest you have a better reason than the need for crude oil, to ensure the uninterrupted production of little plastic covered baseball trading cards.<br>
<br>
Otherwise what you're saying is that 61 million people died in World War II to ensure the uninterrupted supply of Sauerkraut to the world.<br>
<br>
A gas price of under $2 a gallon or the chance to make things right in this world... What would you rather fight and possibly die for?<br>
