<br>
It's not about giving credit to anyone here;  a large part of the EQ community certainly has the wherewithal and, dare I say, maturity to handle such content.  <br>
<br>
But to brandish it as shock value to buttress an argument is an extreme case of using graphic content where it is not wanted, not solicited, and certainly not warranted.  <br>
<br>
If you have a friend, and that friend is murdered, and the coroner's pictures were released on the web, would you not find it disrepectful to the memory of your friend?  If a family member dies and the crime scene photos are published in a public forum, would you not be incensed?  <br>
<br>
There is a certain decorum that must be followed in civil debate and that is respect, for not only your opponent but also those who may bear witness.  I can fully understand the gravity of a murdered child.  I do not wish to be clubbed over the head with it.  I would assume the family of the child would not wish it so, either.  <br>
